stack.imgur.com/pVoco.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14587,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14587/the-nightman","reputation":1330,"display_name":"The Nightman","accept_rate":50},"score":8,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1429659481,"creation_date":1429659170,"body":"<p>A paper was just published that explains this phenomenon in PLOS One, found <a href=\"http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0119470\">here<\/a>. It looks like the sound is caused by the formation of a gas cavity in synovial fluid of the joints. They do mention that contrary to what is stated in the most upvoted answer here, the sound does not come from the collapse of the bubble, but rather its formation.<\/p>\n\n<p>And in response to the comments, as mentioned in the paper, this does not seem to cause any harm to the meniscus or surrounding tissue. <\/p>\n","answer_id":31582,"question_id":19850,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1429659481}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/19850/why-does-cracking-a-joint-make-noise","last_activity_date":1429659481,"creation_date":1406016135,"answer_count":3,"title":"Why does cracking a joint make noise?","body":"<p>What causes the noise when you crack a joint? Is joint cracking harmful? <\/p>\n","question_id":19850,"tags":["bone-biology","joints"],"score":41,"accepted_answer_id":19851,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":3555,"up_vote_count":42,"last_edit_date":1406020319},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e1342c70b82ee050c03a92ffefcd5c16?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":771,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/771/ashu","reputation":413,"display_name":"Ashu","accept_rate":50},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/pVoco.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14587,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14587/the-nightman","reputation":1330,"d