theria\">Laurasiatheria group<\/a> and primates are members of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euarchontoglires\">Euarchontoglires<\/a>. These groups of mammals probably split off from each other about 100 millionish years ago. For more information about mammalian phylogeny, look <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mammal#Molecular_classification_of_placentals\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31541,"question_id":31540,"up_vote_count":8},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":9,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1429580861,"creation_date":1429580406,"body":"<p><strong>\"Evolving from another species\" versus \"Most Recent Common Ancestor (MRCA)\"<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>One cannot say from two extant species that one evolved from the other. It just doesn't make any sense. It is not only true for cats and chimpanzee but it is true for any pair of extant species. One extant species has never evolved from another extant species.<\/p>\n\n<p>However, one can say from any pair of species (Eventual exception with viruses but don't pay attention to them now) that they have a common ancestor. Again, it is not only true for cats and chimpanzees but also for yeasts and ants or for chestnut trees and reticulated pythons. The interesting question is always, \"when did the MRCA lived?\" or if you prefer \"when was the time when the two species (cat and chimpanzee for example) were only one single species?\"<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Chimpanzee and cats evolutionary relationships<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>This question has been by @user137. Cats and chimpanzee are both mammals. Their most recent common ancestor was therefore also a mammal and this most recent common ancestor lived about 100 million years ago. This is the kind of information you can get with DNA comparison.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>How do we know that?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>@user137 already linked to an article that shows when the most common ancestor of cats and chimpanzee has lived. If you want, you can learn more about how such inferences can be made. As you like mathematics (read on your profile), you might be not too scared (although it will take some time) of statistics and algorithmic to have a look at those wikipedia articles:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phylogenetics\">Phylogenetics<\/a> - generality about phylogenetics (=the study of evolutionary relationship between organisms)<\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_phylogenetics\">Computational phylogenetics<\/a> - How to build a phylogenetic tree<\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molecular_clock\">Molecular clock<\/a> - One method to estimate the length of the branches in a phylogenetic tree. <\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>To understand the stats, you may need first to follow a stats course, such as <a href=\"https://www.khanacademy.org/math/probability\">this one<\/a> from Khan Academy but again it will take some time.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31545,"question_id":31540,"up_vote_count":9,"last_edit_date":1429580861}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31540/did-cats-evolve-from-monkeys-or-vice-versa","last_activity_date":1429580861,"creation_date":1429569398,"answer_count":2,"title":"Did cats evolve from monkeys ? or vice versa?","body":"<p>Did cats evolve from monkeys ? or vice versa ?<\/p>\n\n<p>How similar are the genes of cats and monkeys ?\nWhat is the proof that they are related or that they are not related ?<\/p>\n\n<p>Most monkeys climb in trees and there are other similarities but I could not find any evidence on the internet.<\/p>\n\n<p>Do cats and monkeys have a common ancestor ?<\/p>\n","question_id":31540,"tags":["evolution","genetics","zoology","phylogenetics"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":2,"is_answered":true,"view_