atar/a573611497b14937df78b21608dbed72?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":10001,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10001/stefan","reputation":396,"display_name":"Stefan"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1429442872,"creation_date":1418782735,"body":"<p>If I may add to what Resonating has said, when it comes to infections, dry cough is usually associated with a viral infection, whereas wet cough is usually caused by bacteria. The two are treated very differently - dry cough is remedied with cough-supressing drugs (antivirals are rarely needed), whereas bacterial infections are medicated with antibiotics (antivirals are NOT antibiotics) and drugs that help clear the mucus from the respiratory pathway. Treating wet cough with dry cough medications is not only ineffective, it can also be dangerous. One more thing - not all bacterial infections necessitate antibiotics which should be used sparingly because the world is running out of antibiotics.<\/p>\n","answer_id":25952,"question_id":25920,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1429442872}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/25920/do-distinctions-between-dry-tickly-and-chesty-coughs-have-any-medical-basis","last_activity_date":1429442872,"creation_date":1418751447,"answer_count":1,"title":"Do distinctions between dry, tickly and chesty coughs have any medical basis?","body":"<p><strong>Background<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>At least in Britain you normally come across distinct kinds of cough medicine \"chesty\", \"dry\" and \"tickly\".<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Fvu9K.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Questions<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Are \"chesty\", \"dry\" and \"tickly\" coughs always due to microoganisms?<\/li>\n<li>For the types of cough that are infectious, are differences due to different species of micro-organism or the same micro-organism at different stages of its development?<\/li>\n<li>Do the alternative treatments (e.g. levomenthol, squill, liquorice for chesty vs. glycerol for dry/tickly) merely deal with symptoms or do they actually help fight the infection? <\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p><strong>Related<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>A related question is: <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17121/what-is-the-cause-of-dry-cough\">What is the cause of dry cough?<\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":25920,"tags":["pathology","medicine","pathogenesis","treatment"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":119,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1418770758},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kAvbf.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12985,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12985/user1042928","reputation":111,"display_name":"user1042928"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d7c5cbd0c2f965a3712ff687c53f997?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14552,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14552/aaaaaa","reputation":2058,"display_name":"aaaaaa"},"score":0,"post_id":31494,"edited":false,"creation_date":1429424224,"comment_id":52769,"body":"shouldn&#39;t amount of light you detect depend on the excitation power? and total volume, and geometry of reaction volume?..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kAvbf.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12985,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12985/user1042928","reputation":111,"display_name":"user1042928"},"score":0,"post_id":31494,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d7c5cbd0c2f965a3712ff687c53f997?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14552,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14552/aaaaaa","reputation":2058,"display_name":"aaaaaa"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1429426419,"comment_id":52771,"body":"@aandreev Yes it would, I&#39;m sure things like the amounts of reactants wo