igeta I\u2019m uncertain \u2013 a single individual with a mutation does not a species make. That said, speciation can be <i>fairly<\/i> abrupt simply because (separated) subpopulations have to respond to sudden changes in environment."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":3306,"edited":false,"creation_date":1359378785,"comment_id":8508,"body":"I was just remembering that Mules (products of donkey and horse matings) are viable while both parents have different chromosome counts, so there has to be some forgiveness there."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fc54887ecbaba35e17251129e5b78c9a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1486,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1486/bli","reputation":812,"display_name":"bli"},"score":0,"post_id":3306,"edited":false,"creation_date":1361546849,"comment_id":9092,"body":"There are cases of abrupt speciation, I think, when chromosomes are duplicated in a hybrid that would otherwise not be able to reproduce sexually. The duplication restores the ability to form viable gametes (the chromosomes can now form pairs during meiosis: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meiosis#Prophase_I\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meiosis#Prophase_I<\/a>). This is documented in plants, where vegetative reproduction allows survival of a sterile hybrid population until chromosome duplication occurs."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"score":0,"post_id":3306,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423855459,"comment_id":47042,"body":"There are, of course, plenty of examples where different species in a genus can interbreed and produce fertile offspring.  The most familiar is probably the dog genus: dogs, wolves, coyotes, and other species all interbreed: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canid_hybrid\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canid_hybrid<\/a>"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1359368342,"creation_date":1345825546,"body":"<blockquote>\n  <p>but I get lost on the 'border' cases.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Not surprisingly, since there are no borders, and this is probably the greatest misunderstanding: Evolution is gradual. It\u2019s not generally possible to say where a complex feature (or a species) starts and another one ends. We <em>could<\/em> in theory say, for individual mutations on the genetic level, in which generation they first occurred, or when they became fixed in the population. But we cannot infer from these atomic changes where our ancestors started becoming humans. So the whole concept of \u201cfirst human\u201d is not biologically meaningful.<\/p>\n\n<p>The best analogy remains a gradient between two colours. Going from the left, where does blue end and red start?<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/3ltqb.png\" alt=\"Colour gradient\"><\/p>\n\n<p>By the way, you spotted this very well by yourself:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>[if there is no first human] then that necessarily means that the definition of a species is itself fuzzy<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Exactly, that\u2019s the case. For more details on definitions of species, refer to MCM\u2019s answer. But it\u2019s indeed crucial to note that the definition of species (or any other biological classification) is an ever-changing approximation which tries to fit a definitive yes/no answer onto a gradually changing scale.<\/p>\n","answer_id":3306,"question_id":3304,"up_vote_count":31,"last_edit_date":1359368342},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.