d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11829,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11829/falsum","reputation":432,"display_name":"falsum","accept_rate":78},"score":1,"post_id":26411,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2ad85f81981e5365a21d94114f3926b2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11657,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11657/augurar","reputation":1124,"display_name":"augurar"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1420558833,"comment_id":42772,"body":"@augurar I don&#39;t think so. If you open a book on evolutionary game theory, it&#39;s a common place to say that an strategy A is a stable strategy against B but not against C. It&#39;s true that books/articles say that an ESS cannot be bettered by another strategy, but it&#39;s assumed that you&#39;re talking about the strategies that are available in your model -- as opposed to any <i>possible<\/i> strategy (e.g., in the typical Hawk-Dove game you&#39;re only considering two strategies)."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1420487223,"creation_date":1420486635,"body":"<p>A strategy is an ESS against a certain strategy. That is, a strategy is not an ESS in itself. In principle, any pure strategy can be destabilized depending on the other strategies in the game. <\/p>\n\n<p>Retaliators are an ESS against Hawks. The reason is that the payoff of Retaliators against other Retaliators is higher than the payoff of a rare Hawk in a population of Retaliators. <\/p>\n\n<p>Retaliators are not an ESS agaist Doves though. This is because the payoff of a Retaliator against a Dove is the same as the payoff of a Retaliator against another Retaliator (i.e., Doves and Retaliators have the same fitness). For example, drift could increase the frequency of Doves in a population dominated by Retaliators. Depending on the increase of Doves by drift, a rare Hawk could then invade (depending on your payoff matrix). <\/p>\n","answer_id":26411,"question_id":11090,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1420487223},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe7a23921d9cc0ec5421334d2c4acf7b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":13028,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13028/wrf","reputation":1,"display_name":"wrf"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3615/biogirl","reputation":3923,"display_name":"biogirl","accept_rate":89},"score":0,"post_id":27710,"edited":false,"creation_date":1421474901,"comment_id":44765,"body":"Yeah he has answered it in the newer editions...."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1421320053,"creation_date":1421320053,"body":"<p>I think Dawkins answers this in the book as well.<\/p>\n\n<p>The point was that most strategies are not stable because the \"random\" introduction/mutation/evolution of some alternate strategies will disrupt a population of the first strategy. <\/p>\n\n<p>The example was a group of doves being invaded by a single hawk (the conspiracy of doves). Because the hawk does relatively better (by winning every conflict against a dove), than even after generations of entirely doves, the random addition of a hawk (say by mutation) will take hold because the hawk always wins against a dove. Whatever feature/gene that created a hawk in the pool of doves will be passed to some offspring.<\/p>\n\n<p>If I remember correctly, the only stable case was prober-retaliator, since all others get invaded by someone else.<\/p>\n","answer_id":27710,"question_id":11090,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/11090/what-are-the-esss-among-hawks-doves-retaliators-bully-and-prober-retaliators","last_activity_date":1429104343,"creation_date":1382686421,"answer_count":2,"title":"What are the ESSs among hawks, doves, retaliators, bully and prober retaliators?","body":"<p>In his book \"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Selfish_Gene\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Selfish Gene<\/a>\", Richard Dawkins says that retaliator emerges as an evolutionary stable strategy. But I think dove is also a kind of retaliator and so if dove increases,  the hawks and others can exploit them.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is retaliator an ESS? If not, which strategy is ESS?<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Definitions:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>hawk : They always fight hard and retreat only when injured.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>doves : They merely threaten in a dignified way and never hurt anyone.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>If a hawk fights a dove, dove runs away. If dove meets dove they go on posturing until one of them is tired and retreats. If a hawk meets hawk they fight until someone gets seriously injured or dies.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>retaliators : A retaliator plays dove at the beginning of every fight. If opponent attacks, he attacks , if opponent behave like a dove he behaves like a dove. When 2 retaliators meet they behave like doves.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>bully : A bully behave like a hawk until someone hits back. Then, he runs away.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>prober retaliator : He is like a retaliator but he tries a brief escalation of the contest. He is hawk like if opponent doesn't strike back. If opponent strikes back he behave like a dove. If he is attacked he retaliates.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>The pay offs: 50 for winning, 0 for losing, -100 for being seriously injured. and -10 for wasting time in a long contest.<\/p>\n\n<p>Source: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Selfish_Gene\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Selfish Gene<\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":11090,"tags":["evolution","evolutionary-game-theory"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"too broad","is_answered":true,"view_count":610,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1382695097},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2039ee57d6c309dd6644d5d5f6bb9936?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1"