14735,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14735/nandor-poka","reputation":2578,"display_name":"Nandor Poka","accept_rate":75},"score":1,"post_id":31308,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"edited":false,"creation_date":1428929814,"comment_id":52349,"body":"I rather focused on the quantal nature of the release than actual release frequency, because in my opinion that is what the OP is interested in. I do not doubt that neurotransmitters are not necessarily released but <b>when<\/b> they are released it is done in a quantal manner. Also the graph shows that most of the time no release event occured that corresponds to what you&#39;ve described."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1428930279,"creation_date":1428926762,"body":"<p>Neurons encode the \"largness\" of the stimulus in firing frequency. Neurotransmitters are stored in vesicules near the end of the axon. It has been shown that neurotransmitter release follows Poisson-distribution and that usually a single \"packet\" (quantum) is released - this is known as quantal release. Although the actual number of molecules in a single vesicle vary a bit, and ocasionally multiple vesicles may be emptied, it is accepted that for a single AP a neuron releases a single vesicle. \nThese two pages can give you more info and details:\n<a href=\"http://neuroscience.uth.tmc.edu/s1/chapter04.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://neuroscience.uth.tmc.edu/s1/chapter04.html<\/a>\n<a href=\"http://neuroscience.uth.tmc.edu/s1/chapter05.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://neuroscience.uth.tmc.edu/s1/chapter05.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Also this <a href=\"http://advan.physiology.org/content/37/1/112\" rel=\"nofollow\">link<\/a> provides introductionary info on the topic<\/p>\n\n<p>A great image from :<a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1113/jphysiol.2006.123224/full\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1113/jphysiol.2006.123224/full<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/03FgN.gif\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n","answer_id":31308,"question_id":31307,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1428930279},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Ic4na.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14735,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14735/nandor-poka","reputation":2578,"display_name":"Nandor Poka","accept_rate":75},"score":1,"post_id":31310,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428929505,"comment_id":52347,"body":"We should combine our answers somehow :D"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"post_id":31310,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Ic4na.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14735,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14735/nandor-poka","reputation":2578,"display_name":"Nandor Poka","accept_rate":75},"edited":false,"creation_date":1428929852,"comment_id":52350,"body":"@poka.nandor - I&#39;m sticking as often as possible to mass-cited papers in journals such as Science, Nature etc dealing with mammalian models. Quite frankly you delved into the more hidden literature on spider cells. I think our answers are nice back-to-back answers from different perspectives. I did exploit your vesicle explanation - hence the +1 :)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Ic4na.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14735,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14735/nandor-poka","reputation":2578,"display_name":"Nandor Poka","accept_rate":75},"score":0,"post_id":31310,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428929967,"comment_id":52351,"body":"Well yes that is true, an unfortunate thing. I linked it only because I found an example in that, but I&#39;ll look for a more general paper."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1429100619,"creation_date":1428928678,"body":"<p><strong>Short answer(s)<\/strong>  <\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Widening of the action potential increases neurotransmitter release;<\/li>\n<li>Generally, an action potential results in the release of about one vesicle of  neurotranmitters; <\/li>\n<li>An action potential does not have to lead to neurotransmitter release - the chance being anywhere between 9 - 100%, depending on the synapse under investigation.\n<br>\n<br><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p><strong>Background<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Neurotransmitters are released in packets, called neurotransmitter <strong>vesicles<\/strong>: <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/rYYII.gif\" alt=\"synaptic vesicles\"><br>\n<a href=\"http://scienceblogs.com/purepedantry/2007/03/06/neuron-to-glia-synapse-on-axon/\" rel=\"nofollow\"><sup>Source: Science blogs<\/sup><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Vesicles are released via a mechanism involving Ca<sup>2+<\/sup>. When an action potential reaches the synaptic terminal, voltage-gated Ca<sup>2+<\/sup> channels open, which leads to Ca<sup>2+<\/sup> influx. The increased Ca<sup>2+<\/sup> in the terminal leads to release of vesicles.<\/p>\n\n<p>A study by <a href=\"http://www.jneurosci.org/content/17/10/3425.full.pdf+html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Sabatini &amp; Regehr (1997)<\/a> showed that widening of the presynaptic action potential in rat cerebellar cells resulted in enhanced Ca<sup>2+<\/sup> influx, which in turn greatly enhanced neurotranmitter release.  <\/p>\n\n<p>According to a study in rat hippocampal cells it was shown that, on average, a single action potential releases approximately 0.5% of the vesicle pool from the presynaptic terminal. The presynaptic vesicle pool was estimated to be 100 - 200 vesicles, which hence <strong>added up to 0.5 - 1 vesicle released per action potential<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.cell.com/neuron/abstract/0896-6273(95)90336-4?_returnURL=http%3A%2F%2Flinkinghub.elsevier.com%2Fretrieve%2Fpii%2F0896627395903364%3Fshowall%3Dtrue\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Ryan &amp; Smith, 1995)<\/a>. <\/p>\n\n<p>An earlier study of <a href=\"http://www.sciencemag.org/content/262/5134/754.short\" rel=\"nofollow\">Rosenmund et al. (1993)<\/a> pretty much confirmed these findings in hippocampal neurons, and investigated the variability between different synapses in greater detail. They found that the chance that a single action potential released neurotranmitters was <strong>9 - 54%<\/strong>. They reasoned that larger synaptic terminals, or terminals triggered by long-term potentiation have a higher chance of releasing neurotransmitter. Moreover, such terminals with enhanced release probability may also have a higher chance of releasing <strong>multiple vesicles per action potential<\/strong>. They predicted that 54% of release events from such enhanced terminals may release multiple vesicles per action potentials, whereas just 9% of normal terminals may do this.<br>\n<br><\/p>\n\n<p><strong>References<\/strong><br>\n - <a href=\"http://www.sciencemag.org/content/262/5134/754.short\" rel=\"nofollow\">Rosenmund et al. <em>Science<\/em> 1993; <strong>262<\/strong>: 754-6<\/a><br>\n - <a href=\"http://www.cell.com/neuron/abstract/0896-6273(95)90336-4?_returnURL=http%3A%2F%2Flinkinghub.elsevier.com%2Fretrieve%2Fpii%2F0896627395903364%3Fshowall%3Dtrue\" rel=\"nofollow\">Ryan &amp; Smith, <em>Neuron<\/em> 1995; <strong>14<\/strong>: 983-9<\/a><br>\n - <a href=\"http://www.jneurosci.org/content/17/10/3425.full.pdf+html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Sabatini &amp; Regehr, <em>J Neurosci<\/em> 1997; <strong>17<\/strong>: 3425-35<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":31310,"question_id":31307,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1429100619}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31307/could-an-action-potential-produce-few-or-more-neurotransmitters-based-on-the-sti","last_activity_date":1429100619,"creation_date":1428925986,"answer_count":2,"title":"Could an action potential produce few or more neurotransmitters based on the stimulus received?","body":"<p>I reckon that if you would be able to widen the AP width, it would produce more neurotransmitters in that larger time interval. Is that correct? Or does the neuron have a standard amount of neurotransmitters it releases in order to pass the signal post-synaptically?<\/p>\n\n<p>(bonus: could it NOT result in neurotransmitter release, or does the definition of an AP include the release of neurotransmitters?)<\/p>\n","question_id":31307,"tags":["neuroscience","neurotransmitter","neurophysiology","action-potential"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":247,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b4ef4944a1ce49db91aea9bb06321035?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":13456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13456/nikita-bunsen","reputation":31,"display_name":"Nikita Bunsen"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":28569,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423940527,"comment_id":47080,"body":"It appears you are asking about blood clotting time. You should clarify your question to prevent misunderstandings on what the question is about."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcf9d3bdac2c3fa35177730c31b34f79?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6307/canadianer","reputation":6147,"display_name":"canadianer"},"score":2,"post_id":28569,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423940807,"comment_id":47081,"body":"I don&#39;t think it&#39;s unclear at all what&#39;s be asked; it&#39;s not about clotting necessarily."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":28569,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423945283,"comment_id":47082,"body":"If the coloring process is gradual, then the question needs specification as to what the PO regards as the end point"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":28569,"edited":false,"creation_date":1423971278,"comment_id":47085,"body":"Is <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bleeding_time\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a> what you are wanting to know about?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b4ef4944a1ce49db91aea9bb06321035?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":13456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13456/nikita-bunsen","reputation":31,"display_name":"Nikita Bunsen"},"score":1,"post_id":28569,"edited":false,"creation_date":1425424283,"comment_id":49416,"body":"Good Gravy - thanks so much ...while not the answer I seek, very interesting none-the -less"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ae0014e2b5be5ac76e0892cdd6f72e8e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6289,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users